WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.160
[Music] Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. In this&nbsp;
video, we want to start looking at some of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:14.160 --> 00:00:22.920
logical challenges that lie ahead of us when we&nbsp;
want to set up abstract algebra correctly. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:22.920 --> 00:00:29.520
abstract algebra these days is not as fraught&nbsp;
with difficulties as modern analysis. Modern&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:29.520 --> 00:00:36.800
analysis has, through and through, logical&nbsp;
difficulties—abstract algebra much less so, but&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:36.800 --> 00:00:43.040
still, there are some very significant problems,&nbsp;
and today we want to start talking about that.

00:00:43.040 --> 00:00:49.000
Okay, so modern abstract algebra is a 20th-century&nbsp;
development, more or less, and it explores&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:58.400
generalizations of rather concrete, explicit&nbsp;
arithmetical or algebraic structures. And the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:58.400 --> 00:01:05.080
logical weaknesses I would like to frame in terms&nbsp;
of sort of three different kinds or categories.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:05.080 --> 00:01:13.000
So the first one, the one that we're going to&nbsp;
talk about today, is this interaction between&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:19.120
definitions and specifications. It's a subtle&nbsp;
thing to try to enunciate because we don't have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:19.120 --> 00:01:25.200
a good language for dealing with these kinds of&nbsp;
problems, but I hope to give you lots of examples&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:25.200 --> 00:01:31.120
of the difficulty with, first of all, being&nbsp;
precise about definitions and relating that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:31.120 --> 00:01:39.600
to what we actually do when we want to specify an&nbsp;
object that satisfies a given definition. Then,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:39.600 --> 00:01:44.000
after that, we are going to also talk about&nbsp;
the important challenges in going from the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:52.400
finite kind of situation to a so-called infinite&nbsp;
situation without waffling. And then another very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:59.120
key problem with modern abstract algebra that runs&nbsp;
through quite a lot of it is this over-reliance on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:59.120 --> 00:02:04.240
the so-called Fundamental Theorem of Algebra. That&nbsp;
wouldn't be a problem if the Fundamental Theorem&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:04.240 --> 00:02:09.160
of Algebra was really a theorem, but in fact, it's&nbsp;
not—it's more of a dream. Okay, so we are going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:09.160 --> 00:02:15.320
have to face up to the music that the Fundamental&nbsp;
Theorem of Algebra has serious problems and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:15.320 --> 00:02:22.960
how to reframe a lot of the dependence of&nbsp;
abstract algebra on the fundamental theorem.

00:02:22.960 --> 00:02:27.720
Okay, so in today's video, though, we're going&nbsp;
to stick with this very interesting question of,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:27.720 --> 00:02:33.440
you know, how do we define abstract algebraic&nbsp;
objects, and what do we really mean by those&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:33.440 --> 00:02:40.000
definitions with the phrases that we use,&nbsp;
with the framework that we have in place?

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:45.160
So to frame this first challenge that's&nbsp;
really centered on the role of definitions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:45.160 --> 00:02:51.360
in the subject, maybe it's good to introduce it&nbsp;
via this question by trying to identify what's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.360 --> 00:02:58.160
actually the difference between a description, a&nbsp;
definition, and a specification. These words are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:58.160 --> 00:03:06.480
all kind of overlapping, and they have some common&nbsp;
ground, but what exactly do they mean? And when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:06.480 --> 00:03:13.000
we define something, are we really defining it,&nbsp;
or are we rather describing it or specifying it?

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:18.800
And to put that question into maybe a more&nbsp;
explicit context, we could ask this other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:18.800 --> 00:03:25.480
kind of question about how do we actually define&nbsp;
or specify an algebraic structure for a computer?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:25.480 --> 00:03:31.560
So suppose we're interested in getting our&nbsp;
computer to understand what we mean by, say,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:31.560 --> 00:03:36.200
a group G. So we have an idea of what a&nbsp;
group G is. Suppose that we're actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:36.200 --> 00:03:43.080
interested in programming a computer&nbsp;
to understand what a group is in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:43.080 --> 00:03:49.080
same kind of way as we do—what do we have to&nbsp;
do? How do we have to frame the definition?

00:03:49.080 --> 00:03:55.240
So this is a very good question for a number of&nbsp;
reasons. First of all, the role of computers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.240 --> 00:04:00.240
of course, is increasing dramatically, quickly,&nbsp;
and it's going to play more and more a major&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:00.240 --> 00:04:05.640
role in mathematics—that's something that we're&nbsp;
going to have to talk about in the future as well.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:05.640 --> 00:04:12.520
Another reason is that beginner students—students&nbsp;
who are just coming to the subject, who have not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:12.520 --> 00:04:16.880
any experience with abstract algebra, seeing these&nbsp;
definitions for the first time—in some sense,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:16.880 --> 00:04:23.760
they have similar problems as does a computer.&nbsp;
They don't have a prior history of intuitive&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:23.760 --> 00:04:29.840
examples or prior familiarization&nbsp;
with things that they can lean on;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:29.840 --> 00:04:37.680
they really require the definitions to be&nbsp;
standalone and self-contained and precise&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:37.680 --> 00:04:42.280
enough for them to be able to distinguish when&nbsp;
something is satisfying the definition and when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:49.120
it's not. So there's some kind of parallel&nbsp;
between beginner students and computers. They&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:49.120 --> 00:04:56.120
both do not have the kind of intuition that a more&nbsp;
experienced mathematician or student might have.

00:04:56.120 --> 00:05:02.720
So in order to be as specific as possible,&nbsp;
let's consider the relatively simple example&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:02.720 --> 00:05:11.160
of a group and how we might define what a group&nbsp;
is. Okay, so I'm going to give you a couple of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:11.160 --> 00:05:17.600
different possible definitions so that we get&nbsp;
some kind of idea about the possible scope of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:17.600 --> 00:05:24.920
possibilities for defining things. Okay, so we&nbsp;
want to know what is the definition of a group G,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:24.920 --> 00:05:30.640
how are we going to introduce that, and our first&nbsp;
answer to this, answer number one, is going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:30.640 --> 00:05:37.800
be very strongly computer-oriented. So this is a&nbsp;
definition that we might give if we're aiming to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:37.800 --> 00:05:45.560
try to get our computer to understand what a group&nbsp;
is. Okay, so here's an example—here's a motivating&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:45.560 --> 00:05:52.720
example. Okay, we see a multiplication table, and&nbsp;
the objects that are involved are the numbers 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:52.720 --> 00:05:58.280
2, 3, and 4, and this multiplication table&nbsp;
is a way of telling us that 2 * 3 is 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:58.280 --> 00:06:09.040
for example. Okay, so motivated by this, we'll&nbsp;
say that here's our definition: that a kroup G—k&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:09.040 --> 00:06:16.400
now is a natural number greater than one, so&nbsp;
k is one or k is 2 or k is three or k is 39,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.400 --> 00:06:26.720
something like this—so a kroup G is a k&nbsp;
by k array from k with certain properties.

00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:31.440
Okay, so before we get to the properties, what are&nbsp;
we talking about? We're going back to our earlier&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:31.440 --> 00:06:37.080
discussion about arrays, and I remind you that an&nbsp;
array was something like a matrix but ultimately&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:37.080 --> 00:06:44.200
was different. So an array, which we can think&nbsp;
of in this case as being this little 4x4 block,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:44.200 --> 00:06:52.000
this would be the k equal 4 case. So this is a&nbsp;
4x4 array, which we can think about as being a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:59.880
list of lists—so that list followed by that list&nbsp;
followed by that list followed by that list. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:59.880 --> 00:07:07.440
that's what we think of when we think of a&nbsp;
4x4 array. Okay, and this array is called a G,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:07.440 --> 00:07:13.760
and in order for this array to be actually&nbsp;
a group or a kroup, we want it to have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:19.040
certain properties that correspond to the&nbsp;
associativity, the existence of an identity,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:19.040 --> 00:07:24.680
and the existence of inverses—those are the&nbsp;
three main properties that define a group.

00:07:24.680 --> 00:07:28.800
Okay, so we don't need to pay too much&nbsp;
attention here; I just give some kind of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:28.800 --> 00:07:33.040
official definition—it's actually not so&nbsp;
important for us, but let's do it anyway.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:33.040 --> 00:07:39.920
So the first one, which is a way of expressing&nbsp;
associativity, is to say that the group array G,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:39.920 --> 00:07:48.240
if we look at the indexes here, g l sub m,&nbsp;
and here n—so there's two indices that give&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:48.240 --> 00:07:55.440
you the positions of the array. For example,&nbsp;
this thing here would be the 3,4 entry. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:55.440 --> 00:08:01.840
so the statement is that if you look at the&nbsp;
l,m entry and then followed by the n entry,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:01.840 --> 00:08:07.480
so now we're really taking the product of l *&nbsp;
m and then multiplying by n, that that should&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:07.480 --> 00:08:17.080
be the same as the entry that you see when you&nbsp;
look under the l and m,n entry—so g sub l comma&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:17.080 --> 00:08:25.040
g m,n. And that should be true for all l, m,&nbsp;
and n within our range from 1 to k. All right,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:25.040 --> 00:08:32.840
so that's some way of expressing associativity&nbsp;
in terms of the entries of this array.

00:08:32.840 --> 00:08:43.000
The existence of the identity is perhaps easier.&nbsp;
We specify that g sub 1,a,l is equal to l,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:53.080
and also g sub l comma 1 is equal to l for all l&nbsp;
between 1 and k. This is telling us that the one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:53.080 --> 00:09:00.360
object, the number one, is the multiplicative&nbsp;
identity in this group. So the numbers are all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:00.360 --> 00:09:06.120
one to k, and one is playing the role of&nbsp;
the identity. So 1 * 1 is 1, 1 * 2 is 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:06.120 --> 00:09:13.360
and so on. And similarly, 2 * 1 is 2, 3 * 1 is 3,&nbsp;
and so on. And this third property is telling us&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:13.360 --> 00:09:25.320
about inverses—that for every index l between 1&nbsp;
and k, g l,m = 1 and g n comma l = 1 for some m&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:25.320 --> 00:09:31.640
and some n in the range. That's expressing&nbsp;
the idea that along every row there's some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:31.640 --> 00:09:39.960
entry with the entry one, and along every column&nbsp;
there's some entry with the entry one, and that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:39.960 --> 00:09:47.160
telling us that every element has a multiplicative&nbsp;
inverse, both a left inverse and a right inverse.

00:09:47.160 --> 00:09:52.080
Okay, so we don't really need to worry too&nbsp;
much about the details—these are properties&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:52.080 --> 00:09:57.200
of a particular k by k array. The&nbsp;
main point is that, first of all,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:57.200 --> 00:10:05.040
the array is a very specific array involving&nbsp;
just the numbers from 1 to k, and secondly,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:05.040 --> 00:10:13.160
that in principle the properties are very&nbsp;
cut and dried in that a computer could be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:13.160 --> 00:10:21.480
programmed relatively easily to check whether a&nbsp;
given k by k array from k was actually a group or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:21.480 --> 00:10:29.360
not. So this is a very computer-friendly&nbsp;
kind of definition of what a group is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:29.360 --> 00:10:33.160
but it's not the only kind of possible&nbsp;
definition that we can think about.

00:10:33.160 --> 00:10:38.280
Okay, now here is our second definition. It's&nbsp;
a little bit more human-friendly and perhaps a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:38.280 --> 00:10:45.880
little bit less computer-friendly. Let's call it&nbsp;
A2. So we're still going to define a kroup—k is a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:45.880 --> 00:10:54.200
natural number bigger than or equal to one—so&nbsp;
a kroup G is now a k ordered set, or oset S,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:54.200 --> 00:11:01.840
together with a k by k array, say capital&nbsp;
A, from S with certain properties. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:01.840 --> 00:11:06.640
the properties are going to reflect the usual&nbsp;
associativity, identity, and inverse properties&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:06.640 --> 00:11:12.480
that a group needs. But in this setup, the&nbsp;
starting point is, first of all, an ordered&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:12.480 --> 00:11:22.440
set. For example, perhaps the set is the numbers&nbsp;
1, 3, 7, and 9. Notice that we have commas here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:22.440 --> 00:11:28.200
so our convention is that this is representing&nbsp;
an ordered set, and we have braces here—that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:28.200 --> 00:11:34.000
means that no repetition is allowed. So here's an&nbsp;
ordered set which happens to have four elements:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:41.840
1, 3, 7, and 9. And together with that set,&nbsp;
here is an array that's basically telling us&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:41.840 --> 00:11:50.080
the multiplication table that we want to give this&nbsp;
set. So it's an array, in this case a 4x4 array,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:50.080 --> 00:11:59.600
and it's from S, meaning that the entries&nbsp;
are all from our set and, okay, okay.

00:11:59.600 --> 00:12:07.760
So officially, there's a list and another&nbsp;
list and another list and another list,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:07.760 --> 00:12:16.560
and these lists are telling us how we multiply by&nbsp;
1 and by 3, by 7, and by 9, following the order of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:16.560 --> 00:12:22.800
the points or the elements in our ordered set. So&nbsp;
we're using the fact that these things are ordered&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:22.800 --> 00:12:33.920
to give a prescribed order in which we're placing&nbsp;
the rows or the columns of this array. So in fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:33.920 --> 00:12:40.680
this is the group that we have seen before.&nbsp;
This is U10—this is the set of numbers less&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:40.680 --> 00:12:46.400
than 10 which are relatively prime to 10,&nbsp;
things that don't have common factors of 2&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:46.400 --> 00:12:57.720
and 5. And this is the multiplication table mod&nbsp;
10. Okay, now, in terms of the properties, well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:57.720 --> 00:13:02.440
this array should have certain properties.&nbsp;
It should have an associativity property,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:02.440 --> 00:13:07.840
which is the same kind of thing that I defined&nbsp;
previously, and one can define it in terms of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:07.840 --> 00:13:12.520
this array in sort of a similar kind of way.&nbsp;
And we want one of the elements of S to be the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:12.520 --> 00:13:17.880
identity—this is now a little bit different&nbsp;
from previously because we're not necessarily&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:17.880 --> 00:13:25.480
having the numbers here be the numbers one through&nbsp;
something. In principle, this set S can be rather&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:25.480 --> 00:13:33.000
arbitrary, so we need to specify that one of the&nbsp;
elements of S has the identity property. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:37.840
in this case, it happens to be the number one, but&nbsp;
we don't need to have the number one in our set,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:37.840 --> 00:13:43.920
and we don't need to have it be the first&nbsp;
one, okay? Somewhere there's an identity,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:43.920 --> 00:13:48.280
and each element then has a left or right&nbsp;
inverse, and that means that once you have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:48.280 --> 00:13:53.080
identified the identity—in this case one,&nbsp;
but maybe it's something else—then you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:53.080 --> 00:14:02.200
see that every row has a number one in it&nbsp;
and every column has a number one in it.

00:14:02.200 --> 00:14:07.720
Okay, so this is more flexible because we are&nbsp;
not insisting that the actual objects be the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:07.720 --> 00:14:15.320
numbers from 1 to k. And this is in keeping with&nbsp;
the human-centric view on groups that really,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:15.320 --> 00:14:20.000
you know, groups come from a wide range&nbsp;
of different situations. Sometimes we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:25.720
have groups coming from number theory like&nbsp;
this, in which case the numbers naturally&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:25.720 --> 00:14:31.440
are not the numbers one, four—they're the&nbsp;
numbers 1, 3, 7, and 9. In other situations,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:31.440 --> 00:14:37.400
we are considering maybe matrices—the group&nbsp;
elements might be matrices. In other situations,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:37.400 --> 00:14:42.600
the group elements might be permutations.&nbsp;
In other situations, the group elements&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:42.600 --> 00:14:47.760
might be transformations, which are&nbsp;
actually given geometrically. So this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:47.760 --> 00:14:52.880
framework is much more flexible in that&nbsp;
the actual objects that are, you know,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:52.880 --> 00:15:03.200
the basis of the algebraic object, the group, are&nbsp;
in fact quite arbitrary, at least in principle.

00:15:03.200 --> 00:15:09.240
However, there's a corresponding challenge&nbsp;
with this approach, which is that we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:09.240 --> 00:15:16.000
to have a prior theory of osets, all right?&nbsp;
So we're saying a k oset S, but we're not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:22.160
saying that the objects have to come from some&nbsp;
specified domain—we're being open-ended about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:22.160 --> 00:15:29.120
what kinds of elements can be in our set S. And&nbsp;
that means that we have a problem in specifying,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:29.120 --> 00:15:34.760
limiting what kinds of objects are allowed. For&nbsp;
example, maybe someone comes along and looks at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:34.760 --> 00:15:40.680
our definition and says, okay, I've got a new&nbsp;
kind of a group. I'm going to let my S be the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:40.680 --> 00:15:49.240
set of all fish. Set of all fish—that's going to&nbsp;
be my set, and the multiplication is going to be,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:49.240 --> 00:15:58.440
and then I specify some rule, you know, that&nbsp;
the product of fish F1 and fish F2 is the fish&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:58.440 --> 00:16:06.960
F3 which is nearest to the midpoint of F1 and F2&nbsp;
or some crazy thing. Okay, so would we allow that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:06.960 --> 00:16:14.040
kind of situation where the set S is some kind of&nbsp;
set which maybe we don't generally consider to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:14.040 --> 00:16:21.560
an honest set? In other words, we have to have a&nbsp;
prior theory of sets in order to really make this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:21.560 --> 00:16:29.920
solid, and as we've talked about before, that's&nbsp;
in fact quite challenging to first lay out what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:29.920 --> 00:16:37.520
the boundaries are that separate honest sets from&nbsp;
make-believe sets or almost make-believe sets or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:37.520 --> 00:16:43.760
almost honest sets and so on. So although this is&nbsp;
more human-friendly, a computer would find this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:43.760 --> 00:16:51.920
much more challenging to deal with because, first&nbsp;
of all, the ambiguity in the nature of the S,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:51.920 --> 00:16:58.520
and also because there's less structure. We're not&nbsp;
guaranteed that the first element is the identity,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:58.520 --> 00:17:03.880
so we have to search around for an identity—we&nbsp;
don't know where it might be. It's a little bit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:03.880 --> 00:17:11.360
less structured, tougher for a computer&nbsp;
to deal with, but it's an alternative.

00:17:11.360 --> 00:17:16.920
Okay, now here's our third definition, which is&nbsp;
even more flexible, so we're kind of zooming out&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:16.920 --> 00:17:22.560
even more, more friendly in some fashion. So we'll&nbsp;
call it A3, and the definition is that now a group&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:22.560 --> 00:17:31.680
G is a set S, no longer an ordered set, just a&nbsp;
set, together with a function, say m, from S cross&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:31.680 --> 00:17:44.040
S to S, with certain properties. Okay, S cross&nbsp;
S—that means lists of elements of S, two lists,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:44.040 --> 00:17:55.680
so pairs of elements of S. So for example, here&nbsp;
is a set S: 3,1,9,7. This is now a set because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:55.680 --> 00:18:00.960
it doesn't have commas, it's not ordered, so&nbsp;
we can move the elements around and the set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:00.960 --> 00:18:09.120
hasn't changed. And here is the multiplication.&nbsp;
Okay, we don't have an array now—we're thinking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:09.120 --> 00:18:19.520
more of a function from this set of pairs to S&nbsp;
that represents the multiplication. And, okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:19.520 --> 00:18:26.600
typically set theorists like to encode functions&nbsp;
like this, at least formally, with some kind of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:26.600 --> 00:18:34.080
framework that's in this direction. So what we&nbsp;
could do is we could list all possible pairs&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:34.080 --> 00:18:44.440
of elements here and the corresponding function&nbsp;
value of m. So let's say this little entry here is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:44.440 --> 00:18:54.840
telling us that 3 * 9 = 7. That's representing one&nbsp;
particular element in the array that we wrote down&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:54.840 --> 00:19:04.000
before. So now we've encoded the multiplication,&nbsp;
not as an array but as more in sort of a function&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:15.800
point of view using more or less standard set&nbsp;
theory kind of ideas of how to encode a function.

00:19:15.800 --> 00:19:20.240
Okay, so then of course there's the question&nbsp;
about the properties, the three properties,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:20.240 --> 00:19:24.520
and we would have to then say what the&nbsp;
three properties are that this set and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:24.520 --> 00:19:29.160
multiplication satisfy. Again, we have to&nbsp;
build in associativity and the existence of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:29.160 --> 00:19:35.360
an identity and the existence of inverses.&nbsp;
But we could use this language that's even&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:35.360 --> 00:19:40.520
more flexible because now we have just a set,&nbsp;
and we don't necessarily have an order to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:40.520 --> 00:19:50.280
set. And also the multiplication is now a little&nbsp;
bit more unstructured—we just have this function,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:50.280 --> 00:19:58.400
and we haven't necessarily organized the&nbsp;
function into an array. We haven't listed things;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:58.400 --> 00:20:09.640
we've just given all the information sort of&nbsp;
all at once in terms of this big set of lists.

00:20:09.640 --> 00:20:17.280
Okay, so this is just another approach to what&nbsp;
a group is, another way of thinking about what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:17.280 --> 00:20:23.480
the definition of a group is. And now I want to&nbsp;
consider a variant of that. So it's going to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:23.480 --> 00:20:29.360
a very close variant, so we're going to call it&nbsp;
A3 Prime instead of A4. And the actual definition&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:29.360 --> 00:20:35.560
is exactly the same as A3, so a group G is a set&nbsp;
S together with a function m from S cross S to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:35.560 --> 00:20:41.680
S with certain properties. What's different is&nbsp;
that we're going to interpret this differently,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:41.680 --> 00:20:45.920
or we're going to interpret it in&nbsp;
a more broader, looser fashion.

00:20:45.920 --> 00:20:53.920
So here's an example: Now I'm going to consider&nbsp;
the set S which is rotations of a square. Here's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:53.920 --> 00:21:01.560
a square, and I'm going to consider the set S&nbsp;
of rotations of a square. Now, hopefully, you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:01.560 --> 00:21:07.360
know what that means. Hopefully, you know that,&nbsp;
okay, we're talking about rotations of the square.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:07.360 --> 00:21:12.240
There's actually four rotations of the square.&nbsp;
There's the identity rotation, which doesn't do&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:12.240 --> 00:21:21.200
anything; there's a rotation by a quarter turn, by&nbsp;
a half turn, by a 3/4 of a turn, or if you like,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:21.200 --> 00:21:29.000
a quarter turn in the opposite direction. So there&nbsp;
are four rotations of this square. But notice that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:34.640
we haven't really specified what the rotations&nbsp;
are explicitly; we've just said the rotations&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:34.640 --> 00:21:41.920
of a square, and sort of the onus is on you to&nbsp;
know what that means. And then, what about the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:41.920 --> 00:21:48.880
multiplication m? Well, here we're saying that the&nbsp;
multiplication m is composition. In other words,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:48.880 --> 00:22:00.040
the product of S1 and S2, or S1 and S2, or two&nbsp;
rotations is the composition of S1 and S2. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:00.040 --> 00:22:03.600
so you need to know what the composition&nbsp;
is—it means that you do one of them first&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:03.600 --> 00:22:10.560
and then you do the other. Typically&nbsp;
here, you do S2 first and then you do S1.

00:22:10.560 --> 00:22:17.080
Now notice that this is different from the&nbsp;
previous example. Here we're not saying&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:17.080 --> 00:22:21.760
precisely what all the rotations&nbsp;
exactly are and giving them names,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:21.760 --> 00:22:27.600
and we're not saying precisely what the&nbsp;
product of any specific two elements is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:27.600 --> 00:22:34.280
as we did in the previous case. Here, we're&nbsp;
just giving a general rule that allows you to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:34.280 --> 00:22:40.240
calculate the product of any two elements.&nbsp;
So in some sense, this interpretation of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:40.240 --> 00:22:47.720
the definition shifts some of the onus of&nbsp;
creating this group on the reader. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:47.720 --> 00:22:55.600
you are now invited to write down the elements of&nbsp;
this set in some notation that you can introduce,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:55.600 --> 00:23:05.320
and then you are invited to understand what this&nbsp;
composition amounts to in terms of those objects.

00:23:05.320 --> 00:23:10.360
So you can see that a computer would&nbsp;
have more of a difficult time with this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:10.360 --> 00:23:16.000
because a computer would have to know how to&nbsp;
interpret this, and then a computer probably&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:24.800
would want to restate this descriptive kind&nbsp;
of definition into something more concrete,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:24.800 --> 00:23:32.320
either into an array or one of those&nbsp;
multiplication sets that we had in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:32.320 --> 00:23:40.760
the previous example. Of course, there's then&nbsp;
also the question of stating the properties,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:40.760 --> 00:23:45.840
and so we haven't done that, but you know, in&nbsp;
addition to saying these things, we would have to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:45.840 --> 00:23:52.960
specify what the various properties are—the usual&nbsp;
associative, identity, and inverse properties. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:52.960 --> 00:23:59.160
it's interesting that this A3 and A3 Prime&nbsp;
definition—they both actually used exactly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:59.160 --> 00:24:06.160
the same wording, but there was a difference in&nbsp;
interpretation as to what that actually involved.

00:24:06.160 --> 00:24:10.920
So the question is, is there actually an effective&nbsp;
or computational difference between these various&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:10.920 --> 00:24:18.560
definitions? Does it really make a difference, or&nbsp;
are they all really more or less the same? I want&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:18.560 --> 00:24:23.400
to suggest that there is a difference—there's, in&nbsp;
fact, a very big difference, both theoretical and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:23.400 --> 00:24:31.160
practical, between defining a group in these&nbsp;
various ways. In fact, I want to suggest that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:31.160 --> 00:24:37.640
group theory—okay, group theory is very strongly&nbsp;
dependent on which of these definitions you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:37.640 --> 00:24:43.080
choose. Group theory that starts with A1 is&nbsp;
going to be a different subject from group&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:43.080 --> 00:24:51.360
theory that starts with A2, which is going to be a&nbsp;
different subject that starts with A3 or A3 Prime.

00:24:51.360 --> 00:24:58.560
Currently, I would say that our modern definition&nbsp;
of a group, even though people don't spell it out&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:58.560 --> 00:25:05.840
as precisely and carefully as we're trying to do&nbsp;
here, is more in the direction of this third A3&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:05.840 --> 00:25:12.840
Prime interpretation. We are allowed to specify&nbsp;
groups by giving some description of the objects&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:12.840 --> 00:25:20.600
and then some description of the multiplication.&nbsp;
We're not really obliged to list all the objects&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:20.600 --> 00:25:28.640
and then to correspondingly list or, you know,&nbsp;
specify the multiplication in its entirety.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:28.640 --> 00:25:34.760
So that's the general understanding—maybe not&nbsp;
uniformly, but it's the general understanding in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:34.760 --> 00:25:40.560
the modern treatment of the subject that more or&nbsp;
less this is the right definition or the current&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:40.560 --> 00:25:45.080
definition. But you can see that there's a&nbsp;
big difference, or I hope you can see that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:45.080 --> 00:25:53.360
from a computer's point of view, this is&nbsp;
much more problematic, much more ambiguous.

00:25:53.360 --> 00:25:57.160
I want to bring the differences between these&nbsp;
different points of view into focus for you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:57.160 --> 00:26:03.360
by looking at a specific example. So let's&nbsp;
have a look at U12, which is another group&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:03.360 --> 00:26:11.360
of order four. So let's start by looking at&nbsp;
U12 from the second definition point of view,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:11.360 --> 00:26:18.520
which is maybe reasonably close to our&nbsp;
human perception. So U12, by definition,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:18.520 --> 00:26:25.720
consists of the numbers less than 12 which are&nbsp;
relatively prime to 12, and those numbers are 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:25.720 --> 00:26:31.040
5, 7, and 11. And there's a natural ordering to&nbsp;
them because they're increasing, so we may as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:31.040 --> 00:26:37.760
well list them. So here's an ordered set: 1, 5,&nbsp;
7, 11. And the multiplication is encoded in this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:37.760 --> 00:26:46.120
array. The array respects the order of the set&nbsp;
that we've introduced, and here is the product&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:46.120 --> 00:26:53.400
of these numbers—this is basically multiplication&nbsp;
mod 12, but we don't have to say that. All the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:53.400 --> 00:26:58.760
information is already encoded in this array.&nbsp;
And actually, the array is just actually this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:58.760 --> 00:27:05.000
4x4 block here—these columns and the rows out here&nbsp;
that index things are really just for our benefit,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:10.120
but the computer doesn't need it, it just&nbsp;
needs that 4x4 array if it knows the order&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:10.120 --> 00:27:18.520
of the objects. So, for example, 5 * 5 is usually&nbsp;
25, but mod 12 that's 1, and so we get a 1 there.

00:27:18.520 --> 00:27:25.080
And so, okay, so that's a very familiar&nbsp;
thinking of U12—that's sort of what we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:25.080 --> 00:27:30.640
would write down most naturally and simply.&nbsp;
But here, here is a computer version of that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:30.640 --> 00:27:35.893
where the computer has come along and said, okay,&nbsp;
we're going to encode that not with the numbers 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:35.893 --> 00:27:39.880
5, 7, but with the numbers 1, 2, 3, 4. Because&nbsp;
this is a four-group, it has four elements,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:39.880 --> 00:27:46.560
and so we're automatically just going to use the&nbsp;
numbers 1, 2, 3, 4 to represent the objects. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:46.560 --> 00:27:50.720
so basically, the computer comes along and says,&nbsp;
I'm going to call out 1, 2, 3, and 4 and just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:50.720 --> 00:27:57.880
replaces the 5 with a 2 and the 7 with a 3 and&nbsp;
the 11 with a 4. Okay, so there's the same table,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:57.880 --> 00:28:05.040
but having done that, the advantage now is that&nbsp;
the computer can encode the entire group just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:05.040 --> 00:28:10.800
with this 4x4 array. Okay, you send that 4x4 array&nbsp;
to another computer somewhere else in the world,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:10.800 --> 00:28:16.840
and the other computer knows exactly what&nbsp;
the group is—not in terms of its original&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:16.840 --> 00:28:26.800
definition as U12, but in terms of the algebraic&nbsp;
structure that encodes the group structure.

00:28:26.800 --> 00:28:33.760
Okay, in terms of our third definition—the third&nbsp;
definition involved a set, so we now lose the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:33.760 --> 00:28:39.680
ordering; we're not concerned with the ordering,&nbsp;
it's just now a set. So I represent that by giving&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:39.680 --> 00:28:44.480
you the same four elements, but not necessarily&nbsp;
in the usual order. So the objects are 7, 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:44.480 --> 00:28:52.440
11, and 5, and then we have to record the&nbsp;
multiplication in a kind of function point&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:52.440 --> 00:28:59.680
of view. So we have to record that 5 * 5 is 1,&nbsp;
so we can do that by somewhere in this list,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:59.680 --> 00:29:07.480
right there, recording the triple 5,5,1. And we&nbsp;
interpret that to mean that 5 * 5 is 1. So there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:07.480 --> 00:29:16.960
now 16 elements in this set of multiplications.&nbsp;
This is a way of encoding this array in a kind of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:16.960 --> 00:29:24.200
set-theoretical point of view. So we have&nbsp;
the set, and we have the multiplication.

00:29:24.200 --> 00:29:30.920
And now a quite different variant on that: Now&nbsp;
we're going to look at A3 Prime, where we describe&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:30.920 --> 00:29:36.880
the set and the multiplication differently. So&nbsp;
we say that S is the set of numbers less than 12,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:36.880 --> 00:29:44.840
relatively prime to 12. That's a description&nbsp;
of the set S—it's the same set, but this is a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:44.840 --> 00:29:55.480
description of it. And the multiplication M—well,&nbsp;
that's multiplication mod 12. So you need to know&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:55.480 --> 00:30:00.760
something about relatively prime numbers; you&nbsp;
need to know something about how to multiply&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:00.760 --> 00:30:10.520
mod 12 to understand this definition. But if&nbsp;
you do, then I guess you could say that this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:10.520 --> 00:30:17.280
encodes the same kind of information as does this,&nbsp;
but perhaps less specifically, less concretely,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:17.280 --> 00:30:24.800
more abstractly. Clearly, this is easier to&nbsp;
write down, right? We can write that down very,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:24.800 --> 00:30:32.480
very easily, and if we replace the number&nbsp;
12 with the number, you know, 12,497,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:32.480 --> 00:30:39.080
then writing any one of these correspondingly&nbsp;
would involve a lot more work. But writing this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:39.080 --> 00:30:44.280
definition would be essentially almost no more&nbsp;
work—we would just replace this 12 with 12,497,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:44.280 --> 00:30:55.400
whatever we said. So there's some efficiency here,&nbsp;
but we have to admit that we're kind of putting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:55.400 --> 00:31:02.360
some of the specific difficulty in enunciating&nbsp;
the algebraic structure under the carpet,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:02.360 --> 00:31:10.120
or we're imposing the task to the reader instead&nbsp;
of doing it ourselves. We're not really giving the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:10.120 --> 00:31:17.360
group in its entirety; we're giving instructions&nbsp;
for the reader to be able to conjure up the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:17.360 --> 00:31:24.480
group. It's like a recipe for a cake rather than&nbsp;
a cake itself—it's your birthday, congratulations,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:24.480 --> 00:31:32.640
here is a recipe for a birthday cake. Okay,&nbsp;
thank you. That's sort of what we're doing here.

00:31:32.640 --> 00:31:38.520
So there's quite a difference between these&nbsp;
various things, and you can see that if you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:38.520 --> 00:31:44.800
wanted to build up group theory as an intellectual&nbsp;
discipline, it would matter. It would matter very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:44.800 --> 00:31:51.440
much which of these definitions, or perhaps some&nbsp;
other definition, you adopted—especially if you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:51.440 --> 00:31:57.360
were a computer. Okay, if you were a computer,&nbsp;
you would have to have a lot of AI underneath your&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:57.360 --> 00:32:05.440
bonnet to be able to make sense of this kind of&nbsp;
amorphous, rather wide-ranging definition, while&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:05.440 --> 00:32:12.200
if you were a relatively simple-minded computer,&nbsp;
you could deal with this quite efficiently.

00:32:12.200 --> 00:32:18.680
So we're naturally led to some very reasonable&nbsp;
questions as to the meanings of phrases that are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:18.680 --> 00:32:25.960
very commonly found in modern algebra—in fact, in&nbsp;
modern mathematics more generally. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:25.960 --> 00:32:34.520
the statement, "Let G be a group." What does that&nbsp;
actually mean? Yes, it means that G is satisfying&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:34.520 --> 00:32:40.040
the definition of a group, but which one of&nbsp;
our various definitions or interpretations of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:40.040 --> 00:32:46.280
the definition are we thinking about when we&nbsp;
say that phrase? In fact, there may be other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:46.280 --> 00:32:52.440
definitions that are different from the ones that&nbsp;
I've given or other interpretations. When we say,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:52.440 --> 00:33:00.760
"Consider a group G," what do we mean actually,&nbsp;
effectively, concretely? What are we imagining&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:01.640 --> 00:33:09.000
when we say that phrase? When we say, "Suppose&nbsp;
we have a group G," again, that's a phrase,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:16.160
but what is exactly the meaning of that phrase?&nbsp;
And to make that more concrete, we can think&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:16.160 --> 00:33:22.440
about it from a computer's point of view or a&nbsp;
beginning student's point of view. If you're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:22.440 --> 00:33:31.400
a computer and someone says, "Consider a group&nbsp;
G," okay, well, what does it mean? Hopefully,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:31.400 --> 00:33:37.040
you've been given one of these definitions of a&nbsp;
group to begin with, and then you know precisely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:37.040 --> 00:33:44.120
what it means, especially if that definition was&nbsp;
the A1 definition or possibly the A2 definition,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:44.120 --> 00:33:49.960
along with some additional information. But if&nbsp;
it was the A3 definition, you very well may be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:49.960 --> 00:33:55.560
at sea in terms of really understanding what&nbsp;
that means. And I think those comments also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:55.560 --> 00:34:00.120
apply to the beginning student, even though&nbsp;
many beginning students in algebra don't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:00.120 --> 00:34:05.960
really appreciate that. Maybe this is part of the&nbsp;
difficulties that they find with the subject. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:05.960 --> 00:34:11.040
the professor comes in and says, and gives some&nbsp;
rather vague or open-ended definition, says,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:11.040 --> 00:34:16.520
"Okay, now let's consider a group G. Suppose&nbsp;
we have a group G. Let G be a group," and the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:16.520 --> 00:34:22.440
student maybe naturally thinks, well, what&nbsp;
does that concretely actually mean? So once&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:22.440 --> 00:34:29.200
a student has spent some years in the academy&nbsp;
and is used to using this language repeatedly,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:29.200 --> 00:34:36.760
they maybe get some kind of intuitive feeling and&nbsp;
are no longer so strongly required or confused by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:36.760 --> 00:34:42.080
it, but I think beginning students find it&nbsp;
difficult—what are we actually talking about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:42.080 --> 00:34:47.000
when we make statements like this? And these&nbsp;
statements are very common in mathematics.

00:34:47.000 --> 00:34:51.080
Okay, so to wrap up, let me give you&nbsp;
a more complicated example that really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:51.080 --> 00:34:59.280
shows how important these distinctions are. If&nbsp;
we stick with small and medium-sized examples,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:59.280 --> 00:35:04.000
maybe the distinction between these various&nbsp;
points of view isn't so big; maybe we can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:12.440
feel as if we can overcome the hurdles. But&nbsp;
if we move towards bigger examples, then the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:12.440 --> 00:35:20.080
distinctions between these various points of view&nbsp;
become very clear—we see it in very stark relief.

00:35:20.080 --> 00:35:25.840
So let's ask the question: What is U&nbsp;
of Zed? Zed is our favorite big number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:25.840 --> 00:35:34.840
10 triangle, 10 + 23, and we're after U of&nbsp;
Z. Okay, so if we take an A1 point of view,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:34.840 --> 00:35:43.320
the A1 point of view means that we need an array,&nbsp;
a k by k array from k. Where k is what? Where k&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:43.320 --> 00:35:51.320
is the size of this thing. U of Zed is going&nbsp;
to be the set of numbers less than Zed which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:51.320 --> 00:35:57.640
are relatively prime to Zed. In order to find&nbsp;
the number of elements in that Zed, these days&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:58.320 --> 00:36:03.840
you need to understand the prime factorization&nbsp;
of Zed. Without the prime factorization of Zed,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:03.840 --> 00:36:12.200
you have no hope of finding the number of numbers&nbsp;
less than Z which are relatively prime to Z—in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:12.200 --> 00:36:17.840
other words, the phi is the Euler's totient&nbsp;
function. Now, we have seen, right, that the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:17.840 --> 00:36:23.400
prime factorization of Z is something that's&nbsp;
completely beyond us here in our universe that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:23.400 --> 00:36:28.600
we're living in. There's no way we're going to be&nbsp;
able to write down a prime factorization of Zed,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:28.600 --> 00:36:33.680
even though due to the efforts of Joel Suen,&nbsp;
we understand the first eight primes. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:33.680 --> 00:36:40.280
but the next quadzillion primes, we have no idea&nbsp;
about yet, okay? And finding all the prime factors&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:40.280 --> 00:36:45.960
is completely—it's a completely inaccessible,&nbsp;
hopeless problem. Therefore, finding the number of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:45.960 --> 00:36:52.360
elements in this set is also a completely hopeless&nbsp;
thing. And finding actually an explicit array that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:52.360 --> 00:37:00.120
has all those numbers arranged in a nice way and&nbsp;
the multiplication mod Zed—completely impossible,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:00.120 --> 00:37:05.720
like physically, mathematically, theoretically&nbsp;
impossible in our universe. So from an A1 point of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:05.720 --> 00:37:15.720
view, this is a completely undefined object. The&nbsp;
computer just stares blankly at you, says nothing.

00:37:15.720 --> 00:37:21.040
How about A2? Okay, there we have a little&nbsp;
bit more flexibility. We don't actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:21.040 --> 00:37:26.200
have to convert everything from whatever&nbsp;
we started with to the numbers 1 to k,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:26.200 --> 00:37:32.040
but we still have to exhibit the objects.&nbsp;
We're still not anywhere closer to this thing;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:32.040 --> 00:37:37.120
we still can't exhibit all the elements in&nbsp;
here. There's no way we can exhibit all the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:37.120 --> 00:37:40.920
elements. First of all, there's far too&nbsp;
many—most of them are numbers that are so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:40.920 --> 00:37:45.080
big they don't even fit into the universe.&nbsp;
Completely and hopelessly impossible. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:45.080 --> 00:37:49.680
there's no way that this makes sense. So even&nbsp;
a human being that has this orientation just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:49.680 --> 00:37:56.000
stares at you blindly and says, I'm sorry, but&nbsp;
it doesn't make any sense. It's not defined.

00:37:56.000 --> 00:38:03.400
How about A3? In A3, we were a little bit more&nbsp;
loose; we were allowing our set to be actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:03.400 --> 00:38:09.360
unordered, not like a real set. And we were still,&nbsp;
though, specifying that the multiplication had to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:09.360 --> 00:38:16.120
be laid out in terms of some kind of function,&nbsp;
explicit kind of function in a set-theoretical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:16.120 --> 00:38:23.600
point of view. Again, this is just not accessible&nbsp;
to us. But the A3 Prime point of view—ah, that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:23.600 --> 00:38:33.560
quite different because there we're allowed to use&nbsp;
words and string phrases together. We just say,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:33.560 --> 00:38:40.520
"Consider S, the set of n in Nat such that n is&nbsp;
between 1 and Zed, and n and Z are relatively&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:40.520 --> 00:38:50.320
prime." Voila, there is the set S that the&nbsp;
group is supported on. We don't need to concern&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:50.320 --> 00:38:55.480
ourselves with the fact that most of the elements&nbsp;
in this set are completely outside our universe;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:55.480 --> 00:39:01.160
there's no way we can even list them. There's&nbsp;
no way we can bring all of these together.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:01.160 --> 00:39:05.880
There's no way we have any access to this in any&nbsp;
reasonable fashion. But nevertheless, we can write&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:05.880 --> 00:39:12.080
down this phrase in a kind of Pollyanna optimistic&nbsp;
fashion. It's like poetry: Look, there it is—there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:12.080 --> 00:39:24.960
is the set. And what about the multiplication?&nbsp;
That's easy: m is just multiplication mod Zed.

00:39:24.960 --> 00:39:28.720
You can see the advantages in having a&nbsp;
modern point of view on things. If you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:28.720 --> 00:39:33.120
have a modern point of view, as represented&nbsp;
by this A3 Prime definition, then you have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:33.120 --> 00:39:38.960
no problem dealing with U of Z because you're&nbsp;
allowed to think of U of Z in this amorphous,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:38.960 --> 00:39:48.440
ambiguous, poetical fashion. No problem, as&nbsp;
long as no one asks you about any specifics.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:48.440 --> 00:39:55.040
So as long as you're willing to ride over the&nbsp;
actual reality at some suitably lofty level,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:55.040 --> 00:39:59.320
where you actually never get your hands&nbsp;
dirty with, like, dealing with the objects,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:59.320 --> 00:40:06.240
just having this abstract point of view—well, then&nbsp;
you can imagine that you're doing group theory,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:06.240 --> 00:40:13.080
that you're studying U of Z, but your computer&nbsp;
has no idea what you're talking about.

00:40:13.080 --> 00:40:18.320
There's a fork in the road here, isn't there,&nbsp;
people? All right, there's this poetical,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:18.320 --> 00:40:25.680
idealistic, modern 20th-century point of view that&nbsp;
allows us to just write down stuff like this. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:25.680 --> 00:40:33.200
then there's the 21st-century, computational,&nbsp;
explicit, concrete point of view that says, no,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:33.200 --> 00:40:41.800
no, that doesn't make sense. I am advocating that&nbsp;
we think about things in a more computational,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:41.800 --> 00:40:50.320
precise, explicit, concrete form and&nbsp;
give up on the 20th-century abstraction,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:50.320 --> 00:40:56.640
ideology, and wishful thinking encoded&nbsp;
in this kind of object specification.

00:40:56.640 --> 00:40:59.960
So the lesson is that definitions&nbsp;
and their interpretations do matter,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:59.960 --> 00:41:05.760
and this is going to be a very important theme&nbsp;
for us as we develop abstract algebra. We are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:05.760 --> 00:41:12.800
going to have to take very special care about the&nbsp;
nature of the definitions that we're invoking,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:12.800 --> 00:41:17.240
and we want to pin them down to&nbsp;
computational reality so that when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:17.240 --> 00:41:25.400
someone asks for some examples, we can give them&nbsp;
real examples and not fake examples like this.

00:41:25.400 --> 00:41:29.640
This was only our first challenge, okay? So we&nbsp;
still have two more challenges to deal with,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:29.640 --> 00:41:35.160
namely the transition from finite&nbsp;
objects to infinite objects,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:35.160 --> 00:41:39.240
and we'll have to deal with the&nbsp;
fundamental dream of algebra. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:39.240 --> 00:41:44.600
we'll have a little bit of things to say&nbsp;
about those things in our next video. I&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:44.600 --> 00:41:57.240
hope you'll join me for that. I'm Norman&nbsp;
Wildberger. Thanks for [Music] listening.

